info:"Ancient Greek culture and ideas laid many of the intellectual, political, artistic, and scientific foundations of Western civilization. Emerging from the independent city-states (poleis) of ancient Greece such as Athens, Sparta, Corinth, and Thebes, Greek civilization flourished especially during the Classical Period (5th–4th centuries BCE). Greek culture emphasized human reasoning, debate, civic participation, and the pursuit of knowledge, producing major advances in philosophy, mathematics, literature, architecture, and political thought. Athens became especially influential due to the development of direct democracy, where male citizens could participate in political decision-making, though women, slaves, and foreigners were excluded. Greek philosophers such as Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle explored ethics, logic, metaphysics, politics, and science, creating systems of thought that deeply influenced later European and Islamic scholarship. Greek literature included epic poetry like Homer’s Iliad and Odyssey, as well as tragedies and comedies performed in public theaters. In science and mathematics, thinkers such as Pythagoras, Euclid, Archimedes, and Hippocrates advanced geometry, engineering, medicine, and astronomy through observation and logical reasoning. Greek art and architecture emphasized proportion, realism, and harmony, visible in structures such as the Parthenon and in sculptural traditions that celebrated the human form. Greek religion was polytheistic, centered around gods such as Zeus, Athena, and Apollo, with mythology playing a major role in cultural identity and storytelling. Following the conquests of Alexander the Great, Greek language and culture spread widely across the Mediterranean and Near East during the Hellenistic period, influencing Roman civilization and many later societies.",
