        coords: [45, 70],
        zoom: 3,
        region: "Central Asia",
info:"The Mongol conquests (13th century CE) were a series of massive military campaigns launched by Genghis Khan and his successors that created the largest contiguous land empire in world history, stretching from East Asia to Eastern Europe and the Middle East. After unifying the Mongol tribes in 1206, Genghis Khan transformed the Mongols into a highly disciplined cavalry-based military force known for speed, mobility, psychological warfare, and coordinated battlefield tactics. Early campaigns targeted neighboring powers such as the Western Xia and Jin Dynasty in northern China, followed by the destruction of the Khwarazmian Empire in Central Asia after disputes over trade and diplomacy escalated into war. Mongol armies captured major cities including Bukhara, Samarkand, and later Baghdad, often using terror tactics and mass destruction against resisting populations to discourage further resistance. After Genghis Khan’s death in 1227, his successors continued expansion in multiple directions. Batu Khan led invasions into Eastern Europe, defeating Russian principalities and armies in Hungary and Poland, while Hulagu Khan conquered much of the Middle East and destroyed the Abbasid Caliphate by capturing Baghdad in 1258. In East Asia, Kublai Khan completed the conquest of China by defeating the Southern Song Dynasty and established the Yuan Dynasty. Despite their brutality, the Mongols also facilitated long-distance trade, communication, and cultural exchange across Eurasia during the period known as the Pax Mongolica, protecting trade routes such as the Silk Road. The empire was eventually divided into several khanates, including the Yuan Dynasty, Ilkhanate, Chagatai Khanate, and Golden Horde, which gradually became politically separate over time. The Mongol conquests dramatically reshaped political borders, population patterns, warfare, and trade across Eurasia.",
