        country: "Stale Bread",
        season: "Mongol Empire",
        coords: [45, 85],
        zoom: 2,
        region: "Eurasia",
info:"The Mongol Empire became the largest contiguous land empire in world history during the 13th and early 14th centuries, stretching across much of Eurasia from the Pacific Ocean to Eastern Europe and the Middle East. Founded by Genghis Khan after the unification of the Mongol tribes in 1206, the empire expanded rapidly through a combination of highly mobile cavalry warfare, strict military organization, intelligence networks, and psychological tactics that overwhelmed many larger settled states. Under Genghis Khan and his successors, the Mongols conquered vast territories including northern China, Central Asia, Persia, the Russian principalities, and parts of the Middle East and Eastern Europe. At its greatest extent under rulers such as Ögedei Khan, Möngke Khan, and Kublai Khan, the empire covered approximately 24 million square kilometers, connecting diverse cultures, languages, and civilizations under Mongol rule. The empire was divided into several major khanates, including the Yuan Dynasty in China, the Ilkhanate in Persia, the Chagatai Khanate in Central Asia, and the Golden Horde in Russia and Eastern Europe, all linked by shared Mongol political traditions and trade networks. Despite the violence of the initial conquests, the Mongol Empire also created a period of relative stability known as the Pax Mongolica, during which trade, travel, diplomacy, and cultural exchange flourished across Eurasia. Merchants, missionaries, travelers, and scholars could move more safely along routes such as the Silk Road, enabling the transfer of goods, technologies, ideas, and even diseases such as the Black Death. Over time, the empire fragmented due to succession disputes, regional divisions, and the gradual assimilation of Mongol rulers into local cultures, but its influence on global history remained immense through its impact on trade, warfare, state-building, and Eurasian connectivity.",
