        region: "Central Asia",
        info: "The origins of the Black Death trace back to Central Asia, where the bacterium Yersinia pestis likely circulated among rodent populations before spreading along trade routes. The pandemic reached the wider world through the interconnected networks of the Silk Road and maritime trade in the 14th century. A major outbreak occurred in the 1340s, possibly beginning in the region around the Gobi Desert or near trade centers in Central Asia, before moving westward through merchants, armies, and shipping routes. By 1346–1347, the disease had reached the Crimean Peninsula, where it was famously spread during the Mongol siege of the Genoese trading port of Kaffa, as infected corpses were reportedly catapulted into the city. From there, Italian merchants carried the plague across the Mediterranean, introducing it to major port cities such as Messina, Venice, and Genoa. Within a short time, the disease spread rapidly throughout Europe, the Middle East, and North Africa due to dense urban populations, poor sanitation, and limited medical knowledge. The Black Death became one of the deadliest pandemics in human history, profoundly shaping medieval society, economies, and religious life.",
