        region: "Mediterranean",
        info: "The spread of the Black Death into Europe began in 1347 when the plague arrived in Mediterranean port cities through maritime trade routes from the Black Sea region. Italian trading hubs such as Messina in Sicily were among the first affected, as ships carrying infected sailors and rats docked in European ports. From southern Italy, the disease rapidly spread northward through trade networks, pilgrimage routes, and densely populated urban centers. By 1348, major cities including Venice, Florence, Genoa, Marseille, Paris, and Barcelona were heavily impacted. The combination of crowded living conditions, poor sanitation, and lack of medical understanding allowed the disease to spread quickly and uncontrollably. It moved along river systems and overland trade routes into inland Europe, reaching England, Germany, and Scandinavia by 1349–1350. Entire communities were devastated as mortality rates soared, with some regions losing a large portion of their population within a few years. The rapid spread of the plague disrupted economies, weakened feudal structures, and caused widespread social and religious upheaval across medieval Europe.",
