        zoom: 3,
        region: "Europe",
        info: "The devastation of Europe during the Black Death (1347–1351) was one of the most catastrophic demographic and social collapses in history. As the plague spread rapidly across the continent, it killed an estimated one-third to one-half of Europe’s population within a few years. Entire villages were abandoned, and many urban centers were left severely depopulated as mass death overwhelmed communities. With so many laborers, farmers, and craftsmen dying, agricultural production collapsed in many regions, leading to food shortages and economic disruption. Feudal systems were deeply weakened as surviving peasants gained greater bargaining power due to labor shortages, gradually shifting the balance of power away from traditional landholding elites. Social order broke down in many areas, with fear, panic, and scapegoating becoming widespread; minority groups were sometimes persecuted as people searched for explanations for the disaster. Religious life was also profoundly affected, as many questioned the Church’s ability to stop the plague, while others turned to extreme forms of devotion. Trade slowed significantly, and many regions experienced long-term population decline and economic restructuring. Despite the immediate devastation, the long-term consequences helped accelerate major social and economic transformations in late medieval Europe.",
