        season: "Black Death",
        coords: [48.8, 2.3],
        zoom: 4,
        region: "Western Europe",
        info: "The social and religious reactions to the Black Death in Europe were intense and varied, reflecting widespread fear, uncertainty, and attempts to understand the catastrophe. Many people interpreted the plague as divine punishment for sin, leading to increased religious devotion, public penance, and participation in movements such as flagellant processions, where groups of people publicly whipped themselves to seek forgiveness. The authority of the Catholic Church was both reinforced and challenged; while many turned to the Church for spiritual guidance, others questioned its inability to stop the disease, contributing to growing skepticism in some regions. Fear also led to social scapegoating, with minority groups such as Jewish communities in some areas falsely accused of causing the plague through poisoning wells, resulting in persecution and violence. Social order was disrupted as normal burial practices collapsed and mass graves became common due to the overwhelming number of deaths. At the same time, the severe population decline shifted labor dynamics, gradually improving conditions for surviving workers who demanded better wages and rights. Cultural expressions, including art and literature, increasingly reflected themes of death, mortality, and the fragility of life, shaping the later medieval worldview.",
