        coords: [41.0, 64.0],
        zoom: 3,
        region: "Eurasia",
        info: "The Silk Road was a vast network of trade routes that connected East Asia, Central Asia, the Middle East, and Europe for many centuries, facilitating the exchange of goods, culture, religion, technology, and ideas across Eurasia. Emerging during the Han Dynasty of China around the 2nd century BCE, the routes were initially developed to expand trade and diplomatic connections westward, especially after Chinese contact with Central Asian regions. The network was not a single road but a series of interconnected land and maritime routes stretching from cities such as Chang’an (modern Xi’an) through Central Asian caravan cities like Samarkand and Bukhara, eventually reaching the Mediterranean world. Silk from China became one of the most famous and valuable products traded along these routes, giving the network its modern name, though many other goods such as spices, horses, precious metals, glassware, textiles, and paper were also exchanged. The Silk Road also enabled the spread of major religions including Buddhism, Islam, Christianity, and Manichaeism, as well as scientific knowledge, artistic styles, and technological innovations such as papermaking and gunpowder. Powerful empires including the Han, Kushan, Parthian, Sasanian, Tang, and Mongol Empires played major roles in protecting and controlling different sections of the trade network. During the Mongol Empire in the 13th century, the Silk Road experienced a period of relative security and flourishing trade known as the Pax Mongolica. However, the rise of maritime trade routes, political instability in Central Asia, and the fall of Mongol power gradually reduced the importance of overland Silk Road trade by the 15th century. Despite its decline, the Silk Road remains historically significant for linking civilizations across Eurasia and promoting long-distance cultural exchange on an unprecedented scale.",
