        region: "Indian Ocean",
        info: "The Indian Ocean Trade Network was a vast maritime trading system that connected East Africa, the Middle East, South Asia, Southeast Asia, and East Asia for over a thousand years, becoming one of the most important commercial networks in premodern history. Unlike the primarily land-based Silk Road, the Indian Ocean system relied on sea routes and seasonal monsoon winds, which allowed merchants to travel predictably across long distances. Trade expanded significantly from around the early centuries CE and reached major heights during the medieval period under powerful states such as the Abbasid Caliphate, Chola Empire, Srivijaya, and later the Ming Dynasty. Major trading ports included Calicut, Malacca, Aden, Kilwa, Hormuz, and Guangzhou, which became cosmopolitan centers where merchants from many cultures interacted. Goods traded through the network included spices, silk, cotton textiles, porcelain, gold, ivory, timber, incense, and enslaved people. Arab, Persian, Indian, Chinese, and later Southeast Asian merchants played major roles in maintaining commercial connections across the ocean. The network also enabled the spread of religions and cultural influences, especially Islam, which expanded through merchant communities into East Africa, India, and Southeast Asia. Technological developments such as the dhow, compass, and advanced navigation techniques improved maritime trade efficiency. In the late 15th century, European powers—beginning with the Portuguese after Vasco da Gama’s voyage to India in 1498—entered the Indian Ocean and gradually attempted to dominate trade routes through naval power and fortified ports. Despite increasing European involvement, the Indian Ocean remained a highly interconnected and multicultural economic zone for centuries, shaping global trade and cultural exchange long before the rise of modern globalization.",
