        zoom: 2,
        region: "Atlantic Ocean",
        info: "The Transatlantic Slave Trade, also known as the Atlantic Slave Trade, was a large-scale system of forced human trafficking that transported millions of Africans across the Atlantic Ocean to the Americas between the 16th and 19th centuries. It became a central part of the triangular trade system linking Europe, Africa, and the Americas. European merchants carried manufactured goods such as firearms, textiles, and alcohol to West and Central Africa, where these items were exchanged with African rulers and traders for enslaved people. Captured Africans were then transported across the Atlantic in brutal conditions during the “Middle Passage,” where overcrowding, disease, violence, and starvation caused extremely high death rates. Survivors were sold into slavery in plantations and mines throughout the Americas, especially in the Caribbean, Brazil, and the southern colonies of North America. Enslaved labor became essential to plantation economies producing sugar, tobacco, cotton, and coffee, generating enormous profits that contributed to the growth of European colonial empires and early capitalism. The trade caused devastating demographic and social disruption across many African societies, while also creating lasting systems of racial inequality and exploitation in the Americas. Resistance occurred throughout the trade, including slave revolts, escape communities such as maroons, and abolitionist movements in Europe and the Americas. By the late 18th and 19th centuries, growing humanitarian, religious, and political opposition led many countries to ban the trade, beginning with Britain’s abolition of the slave trade in 1807, followed later by the abolition of slavery itself in many regions. The Transatlantic Slave Trade remains one of the largest forced migrations and humanitarian tragedies in world history, with long-lasting global social, economic, and cultural consequences.",
