        zoom: 6,
        region: "Florence",
        info: "The Birth of the Renaissance in Italy (14th–15th century) was a cultural and intellectual revival that marked the transition from the medieval period to early modern Europe. It began in the city-states of northern and central Italy—especially Florence, Venice, and Milan—where economic prosperity from trade and banking created wealthy merchant families who became major patrons of art and learning. Among the most influential patrons were the Medici family of Florence, who supported artists, architects, and scholars, helping to shape a new cultural movement centered on humanism. Renaissance humanism emphasized the study of classical Greek and Roman texts, focusing on human potential, individual achievement, and secular subjects alongside religious themes. Early pioneers such as Dante Alighieri, Petrarch, and Boccaccio helped revive classical literature and develop vernacular Italian writing. In visual arts, artists like Giotto began experimenting with realism, perspective, and natural human emotion, breaking away from the more symbolic and rigid styles of medieval art. The invention and spread of the printing press in the mid-15th century later accelerated the diffusion of Renaissance ideas across Europe. The period also saw advances in architecture, science, and political thought, with thinkers like Machiavelli analyzing state power in a more realistic and secular manner. The Italian Renaissance laid the foundation for broader European transformations in art, science, exploration, and philosophy that would later spread northward and evolve into the High Renaissance and the Scientific Revolution.",
