        info: "The High Renaissance (late 15th–early 16th century, roughly 1490–1527) was the peak of Renaissance art, characterized by extraordinary achievements in painting, sculpture, and architecture that emphasized harmony, proportion, realism, and classical balance. Centered mainly in Rome, Florence, and Venice, this period was strongly supported by powerful patrons such as the Papacy, especially Popes Julius II and Leo X, who commissioned large-scale artistic and architectural projects to display the glory of the Church. The High Renaissance is often associated with three “giants” of art: Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, and Raphael. Leonardo exemplified the union of art and science, creating masterpieces such as the Mona Lisa and The Last Supper, while also conducting studies in anatomy, engineering, and nature. Michelangelo excelled in sculpture and painting, producing works like David and the Sistine Chapel ceiling, which demonstrated intense human emotion and anatomical precision. Raphael became known for his balanced compositions and clarity, especially in works like The School of Athens, which reflected Renaissance humanism and classical philosophy. Architecture also flourished, with designers like Bramante contributing to the development of St. Peter’s Basilica in Rome. The period marked an “artistic explosion” in which techniques such as linear perspective, chiaroscuro (light and shadow), and realistic human proportion reached their highest refinement. However, the High Renaissance began to decline after 1527 with the Sack of Rome, which disrupted artistic patronage and scattered many artists across Europe, helping spread Renaissance styles beyond Italy and into the Northern Renaissance.",
