        coords: [51.0, 10.0],
        zoom: 5,
        region: "Wittenberg",
        info: "The Beginning of the Protestant Reformation (early 16th century) was a major religious movement in Europe that challenged the authority, practices, and doctrines of the Roman Catholic Church and ultimately led to the fragmentation of Western Christianity. It is commonly dated to 1517, when Martin Luther, a German monk and theologian, published his Ninety-Five Theses in Wittenberg, criticizing the Church’s sale of indulgences and broader corruption within the clergy. Luther argued that salvation came through faith alone (sola fide) and that the Bible, not Church tradition or papal authority, was the ultimate source of religious truth (sola scriptura). His ideas spread rapidly due to the printing press, which allowed pamphlets and translations of religious texts to circulate widely across Europe. The movement gained strong support in parts of the Holy Roman Empire, especially among princes who saw an opportunity to reduce papal influence and gain greater local control over church lands and taxation. The Catholic Church initially attempted to suppress the movement, and Luther was declared an outlaw at the Diet of Worms in 1521, but he was protected by German princes, allowing Protestant ideas to continue spreading. Other reformers such as Huldrych Zwingli in Switzerland and later John Calvin expanded and systematized Protestant theology, leading to the formation of distinct Protestant churches. The Reformation triggered widespread religious conflict across Europe, including wars, political fragmentation, and long-term shifts in the balance of power between church and state. It also encouraged greater literacy, translation of the Bible into vernacular languages, and the rise of individual religious interpretation.",
