        zoom: 5,
        region: "Western Europe",
        info: "The Scientific Revolution (16th–17th centuries) marked a major shift in European thought from reliance on religious authority and ancient texts toward observation, experimentation, and mathematical reasoning. One of its earliest and most controversial ideas was Nicolaus Copernicus’ heliocentric theory, published in 1543 in De revolutionibus orbium coelestium, which argued that the Sun, not the Earth, was the center of the universe. This directly challenged the long-established geocentric model supported by Aristotelian philosophy and Church teachings, which placed humanity at the center of creation. Although Copernicus himself presented his theory cautiously and it initially circulated among scholars, it eventually became a source of deep conflict with religious authorities as later astronomers like Galileo provided strong observational evidence in its favor. The Catholic Church, especially through institutions like the Roman Inquisition, strongly resisted ideas that contradicted scripture-based interpretations of the universe. One of the most famous figures to suffer for such ideas was Giordano Bruno, an Italian philosopher and former Dominican friar. Bruno went beyond Copernicus by suggesting not only a heliocentric system but also an infinite universe with countless stars and possibly other worlds, ideas that deeply challenged both scientific and theological assumptions of the time. He was arrested, tried for heresy, and after years of imprisonment and refusal to recant his beliefs, was burned at the stake in 1600. His execution became a powerful symbol of the conflict between emerging scientific thought and religious orthodoxy. The Church’s opposition did not stop scientific progress but created tension that later intensified during Galileo Galilei’s trial in 1633 for supporting heliocentrism. Over time, however, the success of empirical science gradually weakened strict doctrinal control over knowledge. The Scientific Revolution ultimately redefined the relationship between science and religion, establishing observation and evidence as the foundation of natural understanding while reshaping intellectual authority in Europe.",
