        info: "The Scientific Revolution breakthroughs (16th–17th centuries) were a series of major discoveries and intellectual advances that transformed European understanding of nature and laid the foundation of modern science. One of the most revolutionary breakthroughs was Nicolaus Copernicus’ heliocentric model (1543), which placed the Sun at the center of the solar system, challenging the long-held geocentric view supported by the Church and ancient philosophers. This idea was later strengthened by Galileo Galilei, who used the telescope to observe celestial bodies such as Jupiter’s moons and the phases of Venus, providing strong evidence against the geocentric system. Galileo also contributed to early experimental physics by studying motion and inertia. Johannes Kepler made another key breakthrough by formulating the three laws of planetary motion, showing that planets move in elliptical orbits rather than perfect circles, introducing precise mathematical relationships in astronomy. In physics, Isaac Newton’s Principia Mathematica (1687) unified celestial and terrestrial motion through his laws of motion and universal gravitation, demonstrating that the same forces governed both Earth and the heavens. In biology and medicine, William Harvey discovered the circulation of blood in the human body, overturning ancient medical theories and establishing experimental observation in physiology. In scientific methodology, Francis Bacon promoted empiricism and systematic experimentation, while René Descartes emphasized rational doubt and mathematical reasoning as tools for knowledge. These breakthroughs collectively established the scientific method, based on observation, hypothesis, experimentation, and verification, replacing reliance on authority with evidence-based inquiry. Together, they fundamentally reshaped astronomy, physics, biology, and philosophy, marking the beginning of modern scientific thought.",
