        coords: [48.8, 2.3],
        zoom: 5,
        region: "Paris / Europe",
        info: "The Enlightenment (17th–18th centuries) was an intellectual movement in Europe that emphasized reason, individual liberty, skepticism of traditional authority, and the use of scientific thinking to understand society and governance. Building on the Scientific Revolution, Enlightenment thinkers argued that human society could be improved through rational laws, education, and reforms rather than blind obedience to monarchy or religious institutions. One of the key figures was John Locke, who proposed the idea of natural rights—life, liberty, and property—and argued that governments derive legitimacy from the consent of the governed. Montesquieu developed the principle of separation of powers, advocating that political authority should be divided into legislative, executive, and judicial branches to prevent tyranny. Voltaire criticized religious intolerance and absolute monarchy, strongly defending freedom of speech and expression. Jean-Jacques Rousseau introduced the concept of the social contract, arguing that legitimate political authority comes from the collective will of the people, known as the general will. Denis Diderot contributed by compiling the Encyclopédie, which spread Enlightenment knowledge across Europe and challenged traditional authority. These ideas spread through salons, books, and intellectual networks, influencing reforms and revolutionary movements across Europe and the Americas. The Enlightenment fundamentally reshaped political thought by promoting democracy, constitutional government, secularism, and human rights, laying the ideological foundation for modern political systems.",
