        info: "Tomatoes originated in the Andean region of South America, particularly in areas that are now Peru, Ecuador, and northern Chile, where wild and early cultivated forms of the plant grew long before European contact. The plant was domesticated and developed further in Mesoamerican regions, especially by civilizations such as the Aztecs, who called it ‘tomatl’ in the Nahuatl language. Tomatoes were an important part of indigenous diets, used in sauces and combined with foods like chili peppers and maize. After the Spanish conquest of the Americas in the early 16th century, tomatoes were brought to Europe as part of the broader Columbian Exchange, which transferred plants, animals, and diseases between the New and Old Worlds. Initially, Europeans were uncertain about tomatoes, as they belonged to the nightshade family, some of which were known to be toxic, leading to early suspicion and limited consumption. Over time, however, tomatoes spread across Europe, especially in Mediterranean regions like Spain and Italy, where they became integrated into local cuisine. This transfer of crops significantly transformed global agriculture and diets, linking the New World and Old World in a lasting biological exchange.",
