        info: "When tomatoes first arrived in Europe in the 16th century, many Europeans feared they were poisonous due to their classification within the nightshade family (Solanaceae), which includes several toxic plants such as deadly nightshade. This botanical similarity led to widespread suspicion, especially among the wealthy and educated classes who associated tomatoes with illness and death. Additionally, early European tomatoes were often grown on pewter or lead-rich plates; the acidity of the fruit could leach lead from the metal, causing lead poisoning, which reinforced the mistaken belief that tomatoes themselves were toxic. As a result, tomatoes were initially used mainly as ornamental garden plants rather than food, especially in northern and central Europe. In some cases, they were even referred to as “poison apples.” Over time, however, experimentation in Mediterranean regions such as Italy and Spain showed that tomatoes were safe to eat and highly versatile in cooking. Gradually, this fear faded as tomatoes became a staple ingredient in regional cuisines, particularly in sauces and stews. The earlier misconception is now understood as a combination of botanical misunderstanding and indirect poisoning effects rather than any inherent toxicity in the fruit itself.",
